[["Map",1,2,195,196],"blog",["Map",3,4,44,45,82,83,123,124,159,160],"figma-to-webflow",{"id":3,"data":5,"body":15,"filePath":16,"digest":17,"rendered":18},{"title":6,"description":7,"pubDate":8,"tags":9},"From Figma to Webflow: Design to Deployment Without Writing Code","Exploring the no-code design-to-deployment pipeline using Figma for design and Webflow for building and hosting.",["Date","2025-03-22T00:00:00.000Z"],[10,11,12,13,14],"figma","webflow","design","no-code","css","## The Appeal of No-Code Tools\r\n\r\nNo-code tools like Webflow are sometimes dismissed by developers, but they reward serious study. Webflow in particular is essentially a visual CSS editor — understanding it well requires understanding CSS well.\r\n\r\n## Designing in Figma\r\n\r\nFigma has become the default tool for UI design for good reason. Its component and variant system maps reasonably well to how you would think about components in a frontend framework, which makes the handoff to implementation smoother.\r\n\r\n## Building in Webflow\r\n\r\nThe Webflow designer gives you a lot of control over layout and interaction. Animations and scroll effects that would take significant JavaScript to implement by hand can be set up visually in minutes.\r\n\r\n## Where the Limits Are\r\n\r\nThe constraints of no-code tools become apparent when you need custom logic or integration with external data sources beyond what the platform natively supports. That's where understanding the underlying code becomes valuable again.\r\n\r\n## Framer as an Alternative\r\n\r\nI also experimented with Framer, which has a stronger story around React component integration. For projects that need more interactivity, Framer's ability to drop in real React components is a meaningful advantage over Webflow.","src/content/blog/figma-to-webflow.md","ec84f10f747a1deb",{"html":19,"metadata":20},"\u003Ch2 id=\"the-appeal-of-no-code-tools\">The Appeal of No-Code Tools\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>No-code tools like Webflow are sometimes dismissed by developers, but they reward serious study. Webflow in particular is essentially a visual CSS editor — understanding it well requires understanding CSS well.\u003C/p>\n\u003Ch2 id=\"designing-in-figma\">Designing in Figma\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Figma has become the default tool for UI design for good reason. Its component and variant system maps reasonably well to how you would think about components in a frontend framework, which makes the handoff to implementation smoother.\u003C/p>\n\u003Ch2 id=\"building-in-webflow\">Building in Webflow\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>The Webflow designer gives you a lot of control over layout and interaction. Animations and scroll effects that would take significant JavaScript to implement by hand can be set up visually in minutes.\u003C/p>\n\u003Ch2 id=\"where-the-limits-are\">Where the Limits Are\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>The constraints of no-code tools become apparent when you need custom logic or integration with external data sources beyond what the platform natively supports. That’s where understanding the underlying code becomes valuable again.\u003C/p>\n\u003Ch2 id=\"framer-as-an-alternative\">Framer as an Alternative\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>I also experimented with Framer, which has a stronger story around React component integration. For projects that need more interactivity, Framer’s ability to drop in real React components is a meaningful advantage over Webflow.\u003C/p>",{"headings":21,"localImagePaths":38,"remoteImagePaths":39,"frontmatter":40,"imagePaths":43},[22,26,29,32,35],{"depth":23,"slug":24,"text":25},2,"the-appeal-of-no-code-tools","The Appeal of No-Code Tools",{"depth":23,"slug":27,"text":28},"designing-in-figma","Designing in Figma",{"depth":23,"slug":30,"text":31},"building-in-webflow","Building in Webflow",{"depth":23,"slug":33,"text":34},"where-the-limits-are","Where the Limits Are",{"depth":23,"slug":36,"text":37},"framer-as-an-alternative","Framer as an Alternative",[],[],{"title":6,"description":7,"pubDate":41,"tags":42},"2025-03-22",[10,11,12,13,14],[],"frontend-learning-path",{"id":44,"data":46,"body":55,"filePath":56,"digest":57,"rendered":58},{"title":47,"description":48,"pubDate":49,"tags":50},"Working Through the Scrimba Frontend Development Path","Notes and reflections on working through a structured frontend curriculum covering HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and React.",["Date","2025-03-08T00:00:00.000Z"],[51,14,52,53,54],"html","javascript","react","learning","## Why a Structured Path\r\n\r\nThere is a lot of noise in frontend learning resources. Having a structured curriculum removes the decision fatigue of figuring out what to learn next and lets you focus on actually learning.\r\n\r\n## HTML and CSS Foundations\r\n\r\nThe fundamentals turned out to be deeper than I expected. CSS in particular has a lot of nuance around specificity, the box model, and layout systems like Flexbox and Grid that rewards careful study rather than just copying patterns.\r\n\r\n## JavaScript: Where It Gets Interesting\r\n\r\nMoving into JavaScript is where the curriculum starts to feel genuinely powerful. The jump from static pages to dynamic interfaces is significant, and understanding the event loop and asynchronous patterns is essential for anything beyond toy examples.\r\n\r\n## React\r\n\r\nReact's component model took a little time to internalize but once it clicked it changed how I think about UI structure generally. Thinking in terms of state and derived rendering is a useful mental model even outside of React specifically.\r\n\r\n## What's Next\r\n\r\nThe path continues into Node.js, Express, and eventually Next.js. I'm particularly curious about Next.js given how much it has become a default choice for React-based projects.","src/content/blog/frontend-learning-path.md","d67070580ef61168",{"html":59,"metadata":60},"\u003Ch2 id=\"why-a-structured-path\">Why a Structured Path\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>There is a lot of noise in frontend learning resources. Having a structured curriculum removes the decision fatigue of figuring out what to learn next and lets you focus on actually learning.\u003C/p>\n\u003Ch2 id=\"html-and-css-foundations\">HTML and CSS Foundations\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>The fundamentals turned out to be deeper than I expected. CSS in particular has a lot of nuance around specificity, the box model, and layout systems like Flexbox and Grid that rewards careful study rather than just copying patterns.\u003C/p>\n\u003Ch2 id=\"javascript-where-it-gets-interesting\">JavaScript: Where It Gets Interesting\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Moving into JavaScript is where the curriculum starts to feel genuinely powerful. The jump from static pages to dynamic interfaces is significant, and understanding the event loop and asynchronous patterns is essential for anything beyond toy examples.\u003C/p>\n\u003Ch2 id=\"react\">React\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>React’s component model took a little time to internalize but once it clicked it changed how I think about UI structure generally. Thinking in terms of state and derived rendering is a useful mental model even outside of React specifically.\u003C/p>\n\u003Ch2 id=\"whats-next\">What’s Next\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>The path continues into Node.js, Express, and eventually Next.js. I’m particularly curious about Next.js given how much it has become a default choice for React-based projects.\u003C/p>",{"headings":61,"localImagePaths":76,"remoteImagePaths":77,"frontmatter":78,"imagePaths":81},[62,65,68,71,73],{"depth":23,"slug":63,"text":64},"why-a-structured-path","Why a Structured Path",{"depth":23,"slug":66,"text":67},"html-and-css-foundations","HTML and CSS Foundations",{"depth":23,"slug":69,"text":70},"javascript-where-it-gets-interesting","JavaScript: Where It Gets Interesting",{"depth":23,"slug":53,"text":72},"React",{"depth":23,"slug":74,"text":75},"whats-next","What’s Next",[],[],{"title":47,"description":48,"pubDate":79,"tags":80},"2025-03-08",[51,14,52,53,54],[],"nba-roto-tracker",{"id":82,"data":84,"body":95,"filePath":96,"digest":97,"rendered":98},{"title":85,"description":86,"pubDate":87,"repoUrl":88,"tags":89},"Building the NBA Roto Tracker: A Flask and API Experiment","How I built and deployed a Flask app that pulls live NBA data from a third party API, and what I learned along the way.",["Date","2025-01-10T00:00:00.000Z"],"https://github.com/michael-baker-content/nba-roto-tracker",[90,91,92,93,94],"python","flask","api","railway","backend","## Overview\r\n\r\nThis project started as a simple question: could I build a useful sports data tool using a public API and deploy it with minimal friction? The answer turned out to be yes, though the path there involved a few unexpected detours.\r\n\r\n## Choosing the Stack\r\n\r\nFlask made sense as a lightweight framework for this kind of API-driven app. There's no need for a heavy full stack framework when your primary job is fetching data, transforming it, and serving it to a frontend.\r\n\r\n## Working with the API\r\n\r\nThe trickiest part of the project was handling rate limits and understanding the shape of the data returned by the API. NBA statistics data is deeply nested and requires some careful parsing to get into a usable format.\r\n\r\n```python\r\ndef get_player_stats(player_id):\r\n    response = requests.get(\r\n        f\"{BASE_URL}/players/{player_id}/stats\",\r\n        headers={\"Authorization\": f\"Bearer {API_KEY}\"}\r\n    )\r\n    return response.json()\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Deploying to Railway\r\n\r\nRailway turned out to be a genuinely pleasant deployment experience. Connecting a GitHub repo and getting a live URL took under ten minutes.\r\n\r\n## What I Would Do Differently\r\n\r\nIn hindsight, adding a caching layer early would have saved some headaches with API rate limits during development.","src/content/blog/nba-roto-tracker.md","c29dabfbdb6a3885",{"html":99,"metadata":100},"\u003Ch2 id=\"overview\">Overview\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>This project started as a simple question: could I build a useful sports data tool using a public API and deploy it with minimal friction? The answer turned out to be yes, though the path there involved a few unexpected detours.\u003C/p>\n\u003Ch2 id=\"choosing-the-stack\">Choosing the Stack\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Flask made sense as a lightweight framework for this kind of API-driven app. There’s no need for a heavy full stack framework when your primary job is fetching data, transforming it, and serving it to a frontend.\u003C/p>\n\u003Ch2 id=\"working-with-the-api\">Working with the API\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>The trickiest part of the project was handling rate limits and understanding the shape of the data returned by the API. NBA statistics data is deeply nested and requires some careful parsing to get into a usable format.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cpre class=\"astro-code astro-code-themes min-light github-dark\" style=\"--shiki-light:#24292eff;--shiki-dark:#e1e4e8;--shiki-light-bg:#ffffff;--shiki-dark-bg:#24292e; overflow-x: auto;\" tabindex=\"0\" data-language=\"python\">\u003Ccode>\u003Cspan class=\"line\">\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#D32F2F;--shiki-dark:#F97583\">def\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#6F42C1;--shiki-dark:#B392F0\"> get_player_stats\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#24292EFF;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\">(\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#FF9800;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\">player_id\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#24292EFF;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\">):\u003C/span>\u003C/span>\n\u003Cspan class=\"line\">\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#24292EFF;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\">    response \u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#D32F2F;--shiki-dark:#F97583\">=\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#24292EFF;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\"> requests\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#212121;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\">.\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#6F42C1;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\">get\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#212121;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\">(\u003C/span>\u003C/span>\n\u003Cspan class=\"line\">\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#D32F2F;--shiki-dark:#F97583\">        f\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#22863A;--shiki-dark:#9ECBFF\">\"\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#1976D2;--shiki-dark:#79B8FF\">{\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#212121;--shiki-dark:#79B8FF\">BASE_URL\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#1976D2;--shiki-dark:#79B8FF\">}\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#22863A;--shiki-dark:#9ECBFF\">/players/\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#1976D2;--shiki-dark:#79B8FF\">{\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#212121;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\">player_id\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#1976D2;--shiki-dark:#79B8FF\">}\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#22863A;--shiki-dark:#9ECBFF\">/stats\"\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#212121;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\">,\u003C/span>\u003C/span>\n\u003Cspan class=\"line\">\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#212121;--shiki-dark:#FFAB70\">        headers\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#D32F2F;--shiki-dark:#F97583\">=\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#212121;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\">{\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#22863A;--shiki-dark:#9ECBFF\">\"Authorization\"\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#212121;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\">: \u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#D32F2F;--shiki-dark:#F97583\">f\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#22863A;--shiki-dark:#9ECBFF\">\"Bearer \u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#1976D2;--shiki-dark:#79B8FF\">{\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#212121;--shiki-dark:#79B8FF\">API_KEY\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#1976D2;--shiki-dark:#79B8FF\">}\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#22863A;--shiki-dark:#9ECBFF\">\"\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#212121;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\">}\u003C/span>\u003C/span>\n\u003Cspan class=\"line\">\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#212121;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\">    )\u003C/span>\u003C/span>\n\u003Cspan class=\"line\">\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#D32F2F;--shiki-dark:#F97583\">    return\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#24292EFF;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\"> response\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#212121;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\">.\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#6F42C1;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\">json\u003C/span>\u003Cspan style=\"--shiki-light:#212121;--shiki-dark:#E1E4E8\">()\u003C/span>\u003C/span>\u003C/code>\u003C/pre>\n\u003Ch2 id=\"deploying-to-railway\">Deploying to Railway\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>Railway turned out to be a genuinely pleasant deployment experience. Connecting a GitHub repo and getting a live URL took under ten minutes.\u003C/p>\n\u003Ch2 id=\"what-i-would-do-differently\">What I Would Do Differently\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>In hindsight, adding a caching layer early would have saved some headaches with API rate limits during development.\u003C/p>",{"headings":101,"localImagePaths":117,"remoteImagePaths":118,"frontmatter":119,"imagePaths":122},[102,105,108,111,114],{"depth":23,"slug":103,"text":104},"overview","Overview",{"depth":23,"slug":106,"text":107},"choosing-the-stack","Choosing the Stack",{"depth":23,"slug":109,"text":110},"working-with-the-api","Working with the API",{"depth":23,"slug":112,"text":113},"deploying-to-railway","Deploying to Railway",{"depth":23,"slug":115,"text":116},"what-i-would-do-differently","What I Would Do Differently",[],[],{"title":85,"description":86,"pubDate":120,"repoUrl":88,"tags":121},"2025-01-10",[90,91,92,93,94],[],"p5js-generative-art",{"id":123,"data":125,"body":134,"filePath":135,"digest":136,"rendered":137},{"title":126,"description":127,"pubDate":128,"tags":129},"Generative Art with p5.js: My First Experiments","Exploring creative coding through p5.js, from simple geometric patterns to animation and interactivity.",["Date","2025-02-03T00:00:00.000Z"],[52,130,131,132,133],"p5js","creative-coding","animation","art","## Why Creative Coding\r\n\r\nThere is something uniquely satisfying about writing code whose output is visual and immediate. p5.js lowers the barrier to that experience significantly — you can have something moving on screen within minutes.\r\n\r\n## Starting Simple\r\n\r\nMy first sketches were simple geometric patterns. Circles, grids, and noise fields. The Perlin noise functions built into p5.js are particularly useful for creating organic-feeling motion.\r\n\r\n```javascript\r\nfunction draw() {\r\n  for (let x = 0; x \u003C width; x += 20) {\r\n    for (let y = 0; y \u003C height; y += 20) {\r\n      let n = noise(x * 0.01, y * 0.01, frameCount * 0.005);\r\n      let angle = n * TWO_PI * 2;\r\n      stroke(255, 100);\r\n      line(x, y, x + cos(angle) * 10, y + sin(angle) * 10);\r\n    }\r\n  }\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Adding Interactivity\r\n\r\nOne of p5.js's strengths is how easily you can tie visuals to mouse or keyboard input. Making sketches respond to the viewer changes them from animations into experiences.\r\n\r\n## Next Steps\r\n\r\nI want to explore combining p5.js with Strudel for audio-reactive visuals — having sound drive the parameters of a generative sketch is something I find genuinely exciting.","src/content/blog/p5js-generative-art.md","1db4e9b05e06663d",{"html":138,"metadata":139},"\u003Ch2 id=\"why-creative-coding\">Why Creative Coding\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>There is something uniquely satisfying about writing code whose output is visual and immediate. p5.js lowers the barrier to that experience significantly — you can have something moving on screen within minutes.\u003C/p>\n\u003Ch2 id=\"starting-simple\">Starting Simple\u003C/h2>\n\u003Cp>My first sketches were simple geometric patterns. Circles, grids, and noise fields. The Perlin noise functions built into p5.js are particularly useful for creating organic-feeling motion.\u003C/p>\n\u003Cpre class=\"astro-code astro-code-themes min-light github-dark\" style=\"--shiki-light:#24292eff;--shiki-dark:#e1e4e8